article.headline: Xavier 70, Temple 69
article.story: PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Romain Sato scored 19 points and grabbed 12 rebounds and Justin Doellman had 16 points, helping Xavier rally from a 16-point deficit to beat Temple 70-69 Saturday. The win keeps the Musketeers' (19-10, 10-6) at-large hopes alive for an NCAA tournament bid. They have won nine of their last 10 games, though they saw their chance at finishing second in the West slip away when George Washington beat La Salle. David Hawkins had 31 points and Keith Butler had 14 rebounds for Temple (15-12, 9-7). Hawkins fell one shy of the team record with eight 3-pointers in his final home game, but scored 17 points in the first half and didn't have a field goal in the last 14 minutes. When Hawkins, coming off a 41-point game against Massachusetts, went cold, so did the Owls. Hawkins hit a 3-pointer early in the second to push Temple's lead to 54-38, but the Musketeers followed with a 10-0 run to start their rally. Lionel Chalmers, who scored 11 points, hit a 3-pointer that made it 62-60, then hit another for a 63-62 lead, the Musketeers' first since early in the first half. The lead was then swapped on a couple of jumpers, and Hawkins sank one free throw for Temple, tying the score 65-65. Anthony Myles dunked home the winning basket with 1:05 left and Dedrick Finn added a free throw for a three-point lead. Hawkins and Sato then each sank a couple of free throws. Temple had a chance to tie on the final possession, but Hawkins put up an airball from the corner. Antywane Robinson put up a layup at the buzzer, but it wasn't enough. It was Xavier's first win at Temple since Jan. 31, 1998. Temple had already wrapped up second place in the East division behind second-ranked Saint Joseph's and will receive a first-round bye. Temple shot 50 percent from the floor and went 9-for-17 from 3-point range to lead 39-31 at the break. Temple finished with 12 3-pointers, three shy of the most ever allowed by Xavier. Johnn Miller and Rick Brunson each made nine 3-pointers in a game for the Owls.
